Research empirical studies on which SOLID principle violations correlate most strongly with post-release defects, maintenance effort, and change coupling in version control history. Specifically look for studies that mine Git or SVN histories to find co-change patterns that indicate design problems, then correlate those patterns with SOLID violations detected by static analysis. Cover: Palomba et al. work on change- and history-based smell detection, the Zanoni et al. studies on god class defect correlation, D'Ambros et al. on change coupling as a defect predictor, and Yamashita and Moonen on smell co-occurrence. For each of the five SOLID principles, document what empirical evidence exists linking violations to measurable quality degradation: Single Responsibility violations (god class, large class), Open-Closed violations (switch statements replacing polymorphism, instance-of chains), Liskov violations (overriding with stronger preconditions), Interface Segregation violations (fat interfaces), and Dependency Inversion violations (concrete class coupling). Also research whether violations of some principles are harder to detect reliably than others and whether false positive rates vary by principle. Include the most rigorous meta-analyses or systematic literature reviews if they exist, and note where the research base is thin or methodologically contested.
